Rats Data Set Example

Alexandra Chronopoulou

Lectures 9 Example

Rat Data from Weisburg (1980)

An experiment is conducted to investigate the amount of a particular drug present in the liver of a rat: 19 rats are randomly selected, weighted, and given an oral dose of the drug, which is approximately proportional to the body weight, (Weisburg, 1980).

  • X1: Body weight (g)
  • X2: Liver weight (g)
  • X3: Relative dose
  • Y: Percentage of the dose in the liver 



      • rat=read.table("rat.txt");

      Let’s change the names of the data.frame columns, so that it is easier to work with them.

      names(rat)=c("body", "liver", "dose", "Y")

      We first investigate whether the variables with each other are correlated.

      cor(rat)
      ##            body     liver      dose         Y
## body  1.0000000 0.5000101 0.9902126 0.1510855
## liver 0.5000101 1.0000000 0.4900711 0.2033302
## dose  0.9902126 0.4900711 1.0000000 0.2275436
## Y     0.1510855 0.2033302 0.2275436 1.0000000

      Among the predictors, we observe that dose is highly correlated with body by the design of the experiment; body and liver are known to be correlated from the relevant literature. Observe that the correlations between the predictors and Y are low.

      Let’s now plot all pairs of variables:

      pairs(rat)

      Some of the plots indicate that there is a strong linear relationship between the two variables, e.g. liver vs. dose. Their linear dependence was know from the literature, verified in the correlation matrix and seen here as well.

      How many sub-models we can fit on this data? Seven, or Eight (if including the intercept-only model).


      Models with one predictor: Y ~ body, Y ~ liver, Y ~ dose.

      A summary of all the diagnostic plots.

      Check for high-leverage points

      library(faraway)
lev=influence(fit)$hat
halfnorm(lev, 4, ylab="Leverages")

      n=dim(rats)[1]; # sample size
p=4

# Determine which leverages exceed the 2p/n threshold
newlev = lev[lev>2*p/n]
newlev
      ##         1         2         3         5         8        12        13        16 
## 0.1779827 0.1793410 0.8509146 0.3915382 0.2536745 0.1723960 0.3161834 0.2166146 
##        17        19 
## 0.1952244 0.1779618

      We have about 10 observations that exceed the 2p/n thrshold and thus are considered as high leverage points. Observation 3 is far from the rest and is flagged in the halfnorm plot.


      Check for outliers

      sr.ex=rstudent(fit); 
sort(sr.ex, decreasing=TRUE)[1:5]
      ##        19         1        18         3         7 
## 2.1388332 1.9170719 0.8426711 0.7972915 0.7774937
      qt(0.05/(19*2), 14) 
      ## [1] -3.64871

      None o the studentized residuals is higher (in absolute value) than the \(t\) distribution threshold, so we conclude that there are no outliers.


      Check for high-influential points

      cook = cooks.distance(fit)
halfnorm(cook, 4, ylab="Cook's distances")

      max(cook)
      ## [1] 0.929616
      which.max(cook)
      ## 3 
## 3

      The threshold for Cook’s distance is 1 and this is on the boundary. So,observation 3 might be considered an influential point.

      As we can see, the 3rd sample keeps being flagged as an unusual observation. Let’s take a look of the data.

      If we compare the models with and without the 3rd observation, we see a difference in the statistical significance of the model parameters. This happens because we identified observation 3 as an influential point, which means that it affects the structure of the fitted model.
